[Event "Budapest — the Peruvian Immortal"]
[Site "Budapest"]
[Date "1934.??.??"]
[White "Esteban Canal"]
[Black "NN"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Blurb "A casual game by the Peruvian master Esteban Canal that became immortal. He gives up both rooks and then his queen, and mates with a single quiet bishop move."]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 c6 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. Bf4 e6 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Bb4
9. Be2 Nd7 10. a3 O-O-O {Both sides castle long into what looks like a normal game.}
11. axb4 {Canal grabs the bishop, offering the a1-rook.} Qxa1+ 12. Kd2 Qxh1 {Black greedily takes both rooks — and walks into a mating net.}
13. Qxc6+ {The queen sacrifice that made the game famous.} bxc6 14. Ba6# {Checkmate by one bishop, with two rooks and the queen given up along the way.}
